%h3="AngularJS"
%p
  Modern web development is simply awesome.  Lots of toolkits with my favorite being 
  %a{:href=>"http://angularjs.org"}="AngularJS."
  Moving the Model-View-Controller to the browser was a fantastic idea.  Not only do I get to take advantage of remote CPUs, but I also can provide a fluid user-experience without context switches.
  %br
  %br

%h3="Ruby"
%p
  %span{:style=>"font-style: italic;"}
    “One's first love is always perfect until one meets one's second love.”
  %br
  %br
  Perl was that first love for me.  I spent hours learning how to use $_ and diamond operators and all sorts of fun obfuscated things.  I also learned all sorts of other languages like Java, Python, C++, Qt...  Then I found Ruby which I had avoided for years(who needs another scripting language).  What I found was a very fun and agile language.  The speed of coding, engaged community and maturity is very nice.  Also, 
  %a{:href=>"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain-specific_language"}="DSLs (Domain-Specific Language)" 
  are simply awesome.
  %br
  %br

%h3="JMeter"
%p
  %a{:href=>"http://jmeter.apache.org"}="JMeter"
  and I are very old friends.  For performance testing, it is hard to beat.  In addition to using in my dayjob, I have also added functionality to JMeter including the 
  %a{:href=>"http://jmeter.apache.org/usermanual/component_reference.html#setUp_Thread_Group"}="setUp and tearDown"
  thread groups and
  %a{:href=>"http://jmeter.apache.org/usermanual/component_reference.html#Test_Fragment"}="test fragment"
  support.
  
  %br
  %br

%h3="Data Driven Documents"
%p
